@article{leekAdaptiveProceduresPsychophysical2001,
  title = {Adaptive Procedures in Psychophysical Research},
  author = {Leek, Marjorie R.},
  date = {2001-11},
  journaltitle = {Perception and Psychophysics},
  shortjournal = {Percept. Psychophys.},
  doi = {10.3758/BF03194543},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: The study of sensation and perception in humans and other animals presents significant challenges regarding expense and methodology, with Gustav Fechner recognizing in 1860 that inner consciousness could be measured through outward behavior, which defines the purview of psychophysics as the measurement of behavior interpreted as an indirect measure of perception. Over more than a century, methodologies have been refined to systematically explore sensory limits, aiming for valid reflections of sensory events through structured observation of responses to carefully constructed stimuli where changes in stimulus strength correlate with detection or discrimination abilities, constituting a psychometric function that is typically characterized by a complete sampling using the method of constant stimuli, though this classical approach requires many samples across a range of strengths to define the function accurately. While the method of constant stimuli assumes a continuous function along the stimulus axis with monotonic increases in performance, often only specific parameters like threshold location or slope are needed to summarize perception, yet extracting a single point from a fully sampled function is expensive in terms of experiment time due to non-informative trials placed at off-threshold levels, prompting the development of adaptive psychometric procedures designed to address this inefficiency by determining trial placement based on previous outcomes to maximize efficiency without sacrificing accuracy. The origins of these systematic adaptive algorithms trace back to clinical roots in audiology developed during World War II, such as the Hughson and Westlake method for searching auditory thresholds by increasing sound levels until a positive response was exhibited, later modified by Carhart and Jerger to include descending searches, alongside Bekesy tracking which utilized a mechanical arm driven by patient listening to continuously changing tones to mark intensity-scaled graphs where the threshold was defined as the midpoint of tracings. These clinical beginnings evolved into modern research methodologies starting in the 1940s through the work of Dixon and Mood who investigated simple adaptive procedures known as staircases that collect threshold estimates from both ascending and descending series, differing from earlier clinical techniques by refining the method of limits without requiring responses to a complete set of levels. Currently, widely used adaptive methods fall into three general categories defined by their trial placement systems and outcome estimation: parameter estimation by sequential testing (PEST), maximum-likelihood procedures, and staircase procedures, each involving systematic manipulation of stimulus levels along experimental dimensions including step size, initial starting value, tracking algorithm, and stopping rules. PEST, described by Taylor and Creelman in 1967, uses changing step sizes to focus the adaptive track ever more finely, terminating when a criterion step size is reached, with the final estimate taken as the last value determined, achieving an efficiency of about 40\% to 50\% relative to an ideal device, though modifications like Hall's hybrid procedure allow for constructing a psychometric function from all gathered data to estimate both threshold and slope. Maximum-likelihood procedures differ by consulting the current best estimate of the underlying psychometric function after every trial to drive stimulus placement, utilizing ogival functions like logistic or Weibull curves fitted to collected data, with notable implementations including Pentland's best PEST, Watson and Pelli's QUEST procedure which achieved 84\% efficiency by incorporating prior knowledge, and Green's maximum-likelihood procedure which promises reliable threshold estimates in as few as 12 to 24 trials by visiting the most likely psychometric function at the target performance level. Staircase procedures offer simplicity and flexibility, generally using previous responses to select next trial placements and estimating thresholds by averaging levels at direction reversals, with simple up-down staircases targeting the 50\% performance level, while transformed methods described by Levitt in 1971 allow targeting of specific locations like 70.7\% or 79.4\% correct by altering sequences of positive and negative responses, and Kaernbach's weighted procedure further allows targeting any performance level by varying step sizes rather than response sequences. Although adaptive methods traditionally focus on measuring a single point to estimate threshold, the slope of the psychometric function is also useful for defining the shape of the function, leading to procedures like those by Watt and Andrews using probit fits, King-Smith and Rose employing Bayesian multiplication of likelihood functions to converge on both threshold and slope simultaneously, and Kontsevich and Tyler proposing cost factors to minimize variance in two-dimensional probability distributions, though reconstructing slopes from standard adaptive tracks often requires long runs exceeding 200 trials to avoid bias attributed to asymmetry in trial distribution or the sequential aspects of the algorithm itself. Violations of assumptions regarding stability over time and monotonicity of the relationship between stimulus strength and performance pose challenges, as subjects may experience perceptual learning or attentional lapses causing threshold shifts, which can be monitored using multiple interleaved adaptive tracks to assess variability within and across tracks, while heterogeneity in stimuli sets, particularly with complex speech recognition tasks, leads to inappropriate trial placement and increased variability compared to homogenous stimuli like pure tones. Comparisons of these procedures via computer simulations and human subject experiments indicate that while differences in accuracy are often small, maximum-likelihood procedures converge fastest making them suitable for infants or animals, whereas staircase procedures require fewer assumptions but may exhibit bias in short runs or with 2AFC tasks targeting low performance levels, with consensus suggesting that 3AFC or 4AFC tasks are generally more efficient and less biased than 2AFC tasks, especially when paired with higher performance targets. In conclusion, the three reviewed categories offer distinct advantages where PEST provides rapid convergence with few assumptions, maximum-likelihood methods offer speed and full data utilization but require computational intensity and shape assumptions, and staircase methods provide simplicity and flexibility, with researchers advised to avoid 2AFC procedures paired with low targets, ensure stimulus homogeneity, and utilize thoughtful parameter selection to compensate for inherent biases while realizing significant time savings over nonadaptive testing.}
}

@article{lenziAnomalousDiffusionTransport2016,
  title = {Anomalous Diffusion and Transport in Heterogeneous Systems Separated by a Membrane},
  author = {Lenzi, E. K. and Ribeiro, H. V. and Tateishi, A. A. and Zola, R. S. and Evangelista, L. R.},
  date = {2016-11},
  journaltitle = {Proceedings of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences},
  shortjournal = {Proc. R. Soc. A: Math. Phys. Eng. Sci.},
  doi = {10.1098/rspa.2016.0502},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: This research paper investigates the anomalous diffusion and transport phenomena within heterogeneous systems partitioned by a semipermeable membrane, employing a theoretical framework that integrates fractional diffusion equations in the bulk regions with kinetic equations governing the membrane interface to characterize the barrier as an interface between two distinct media. The study posits that particle dynamics are controlled by these fractional equations which incorporate memory effects through convolutions between reaction rates and densities to account for anomalous diffusion and non-Debye relaxations, resulting in a rich variety of behaviors for particle distribution at the interface and in the bulk contingent upon the choice of characteristic times in the boundary conditions and the fractional index of the modelling equations. In the introduction, the authors emphasize the fundamental role of membranes in biology and engineering as selective barriers and transporters where complex permeability arises from sorption, desorption, and translocation processes, noting that conventional diffusion models are often inadequate because real systems frequently exhibit anomalous diffusion marked by a nonlinear mean square displacement proportional to time raised to a power alpha, indicative of non-Markovian stochastic processes or long-tailed L\'evy distributions. To address these complexities, the formalism modifies both kinetic and boundary conditions by incorporating convolutions leading to memory effects alongside fractional diffusion equations that describe the bulk particle dynamics, specifically considering an infinite medium divided at x=0 by a sufficiently thin membrane separating two regions where particle densities satisfy fractional diffusion equations utilizing Riemann--Liouville time derivatives with fractional indices between zero and one to represent subdiffusive processes. The boundary conditions couple the current density from both sides to the time variation of sorbed surface densities and transport rates through integral kernels, extending the Langmuir approximation to non-usual relaxations by introducing time-dependent rate kernels associated with surface irregularities, macromolecular crowding, or fractal nature, while ensuring that the conservation of total particles is maintained across the system through coupled differential-integral equations derived from the integration of the bulk diffusion equations. Analytical solutions are established using the Laplace transform and Green function approach, yielding expressions involving special functions such as the Fox H function and the Mittag--Leffler function, which capture the anomalous relaxation inherent in the system due to the presence of fractional time derivatives. Numerical analysis of specific cases reveals rich diffusive regimes; for instance, under unidirectional transport conditions where k2 equals zero, the mean square displacement in the receiving region asymptotically approaches a regime governed by the bulk fractional index, while intermediate times display transient behaviors influenced by the membrane acting as an obstacle during the passage from one side to the other. Comparisons between scenarios with and without reverse sorption processes demonstrate that the presence of adsorption and desorption can induce anomalous diffusion in the source region over long times due to particle crowding, whereas allowing reverse transport may lead to the recovery of usual diffusion asymptotically in the source region depending on the specific kinetic parameters, with the spreading of the system in region 2 being governed by a combination of alpha1 and alpha2 in contrast to cases where only alpha2 dominates. Ultimately, the discussion concludes that the interplay between bulk properties and membrane interface dynamics generates a diverse array of diffusive behaviors including transient superdiffusive, usual, and subdiffusive regimes, offering a generalizable model capable of describing complex transport in biological contexts such as cell membranes where molecular crowding and viscosity result in diffusion orders of magnitude slower than predicted by classical theories.}
}

@article{levittTransformedUpdownMethods1971,
  title = {Transformed Up-down Methods in Psychoacoustics},
  author = {Levitt, H.},
  date = {1971-02-01},
  journaltitle = {Journal of the Acoustical Society of America},
  shortjournal = {J. Acoust. Soc. Am.},
  doi = {10.1121/1.1912375},
  issue = {2B},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: H. Levitt presents a comprehensive overview of transformed up-down methods in psychoacoustics, emphasizing their advantages in parameter estimation and efficient observation placement compared to conventional techniques, noting that these adaptive procedures determine stimulus levels based on preceding stimuli and responses within the broader class of sequential experiments where data dictates the experimental course. The paper defines the psychometric function through location parameters like X50 and spread parameters like DL, often modeled as cumulative normal distributions, and outlines basic assumptions including monotonicity, stationarity, parametric form, and response independence, though only monotonicity is strictly essential for up-down methods while good observation placement near the target parameter is prioritized over sophisticated estimation on poorly placed data. Conventional methods such as the method of constants involve pre-selected randomized stimulus levels allowing for curve fitting via probit or logit analysis but suffer from inefficiency when estimating single points due to observations distributed away from the region of interest, inability to account for parameter drift during testing, and susceptibility to bias in slope estimates with small samples, whereas the method of limits uses fixed step adjustments upon reversal to provide rapid estimates of X50 but places observations poorly relative to the threshold and introduces bias dependent on step size and initial conditions. The simple up-down or staircase method improves efficiency by placing most observations near X50 through reversals after positive or negative responses, continuing until multiple reversals occur to ensure stability, utilizing mid-run averages of peaks and valleys for robust estimation while step sizes can be reduced systematically using rules like Robbins-Monro to optimize convergence variance, though practical implementation often involves halving step sizes after specific runs to manage equipment complexity and interleaving multiple strategies at random prevents subject anticipation while allowing tracking of gradual drifts in parameter values. The transformed up-down procedure extends applicability beyond X50 by categorizing response sequences into UP and DOWN groups to converge on other percentile points such as X70 or X84, defined by groupings in Table I where stimulus changes occur only after specific sequence probabilities equalize, effectively creating a transformed response curve analogous to the standard psychometric function for the simple method, and by employing strategies targeting symmetric points around X50 like X15.9 and X84.1 researchers can estimate both location and scale parameters simultaneously with high precision while interleaving ensures subjects cannot predict the rule and specific transformations can extend the symmetric region of the response curve for applications like intelligibility testing. Practical applications include tracking gradual drifts in auditory detection parameters and compensating for reference plane changes in lateralization studies, where comparing estimates of spread derived from different percentile pairs validates precision predictions regarding observation placement, and in detection tasks response curve asymmetry can affect estimation precision necessitating careful strategy selection while interleaving identical strategies allows for the detection of sequential response dependencies by comparing estimates derived from trials following positive versus negative previous responses using transitional response curves to evaluate performance when independence assumptions are violated. Adaptive procedures offer significant advantages including higher efficiency, greater flexibility, and reduced reliance on restrictive assumptions compared to conventional methods, particularly regarding the ability to track parameter drifts or compensate for trends while estimating others, and while maximum efficiency is theoretically achievable through complex computer-assisted algorithms well-designed up-down procedures achieve within 30\% of this potential with much simpler instrumentation making them highly suitable for limited-duration psychoacoustic experiments where assumptions may be suspect. The distinction between observation placement and estimation remains critical as poor placement cannot be corrected statistically though ancillary information like confidence ratings can improve placement without complicating the core estimation algorithm, and ultimately no single optimum procedure exists but transformed up-down methods provide a flexible robust family of techniques adaptable to specific experimental requirements without heavy dependency on underlying assumptions.}
}

@article{loewensteinMechanicalTransmissionPacinian1966,
  title = {Mechanical Transmission in a Pacinian Corpuscle. {{An}} Analysis and a Theory},
  author = {Loewenstein, W. R. and Skalak, R.},
  date = {1966-01},
  journaltitle = {Journal of Physiology},
  shortjournal = {J. Physiol.},
  doi = {10.1113/jphysiol.1966.sp007827},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: This study presents a comprehensive analysis of mechanical force transmission through the Pacinian corpuscle to explain the generation of sensory nerve excitation, identifying the primary structural elements involved as the lamellae, their interconnections, and the interlamellar fluid which function respectively as elastic elements, constraints for the fluid, and viscous elements within a mechanical equivalent system comprising dashpots and springs that operates as a mechanical filter suppressing low frequencies. Under static compression, the analysis reveals that only elastic forces exist, yet these are transmitted poorly from the periphery to the center due to the high compliance of lamellar interconnections relative to the lamellae themselves, causing most pressure loads to be carried by outer lamellae and leaving only a small fraction of steady-state pressure at the sensory ending, thereby establishing the mechanical basis for receptor adaptation, whereas under dynamic compression viscous forces develop and account for most pressure early in the process before elastic deformations fully develop, allowing for efficient transmission where pressure differences near the center remain comparable to those at the periphery throughout compression, explaining the marked velocity dependence of the generator response. When compression is held fixed after the dynamic phase, pressure differences at the center fall abruptly to near zero, matching the duration of the active phase of the generator current and confirming that the mechanical filter action is the rate-limiting factor in adaptation, while upon release from compression energy stored in elastic elements is consumed in viscous flow producing new viscous pressure dependent on release velocity with a pressure distribution rotated ninety degrees relative to compression but eliciting a generator response of identical polarity and magnitude order accounting for the off-response in purely mechanical terms. The study employs both spherical and cylindrical models, with the latter using concentric cylindrical membranes representing the core and lamellae assuming the core is relatively rigid based on previous deflexion data, utilizing Fourier series for pressure distributions and deriving equations of motion considering lamella compliance radial spring stress and viscous fluid resistance neglecting inertia due to low Reynolds numbers. An electrical analogue is constructed mapping pressure to voltage displacement to charge and velocity to current allowing the use of standard network theory to compute solutions for displacement and pressure across thirty lamellar units with numerical examples utilizing dimensions typical for cat mesentery corpuscles assuming fluid properties similar to water and tissue elasticity similar to arterial walls with computations performed on an IBM 7094 computer covering static displacement steady-state frequency responses and transient responses via finite difference techniques. Computed static displacements decrease rapidly with radius and become nearly zero near the core agreeing qualitatively with Hubbard's experimental measurements while dynamic displacement curves reproduce the features of experimental values sufficiently to validate the underlying concepts and computed static pressure on the core is found to be only a small fraction of that on the outermost lamella primarily due to the stiffness preponderance of lamellae over radial connexions constituting the basis for adaptation under static loading. Dynamic pressure computations for sinusoidal and linear stimulation demonstrate that at high frequencies the pressure on the core approaches the applied pressure due to viscous action corresponding to resistive elements predominating over capacitive impedance in the electrical analogue whereas at zero frequency the pressure is minimal and during sudden release from static compression the core pressure rises abruptly due to passive elastic return determining the rate-limiting factor generating a negative pressure peak that decays within milliseconds as velocities decrease mirroring the physiological off-response. These findings illuminate receptor adaptation mechanisms showing that the wide-spread phenomenon manifests as decreased electrical output amplitude with decreasing stimulus velocity because static loading produces little central pressure while dynamic phases propagate pressure well via viscous action and experiments on decapsulated corpuscles bypassing the peripheral lamellae filter confirm that the capsule's filter action is the rate-limiting factor for decay in generator potential as decapsulated receptors show prolonged generator potentials and lack off-responses. The theory attributes the off-response entirely to mechanical properties of the capsule where elastic lamellae store energy supplied by external stimuli releasing it upon decompression to drive viscous flow while the velocity dependence of the generator response is explained by the capsule acting like a series of dashpot pistons generating viscous pressure and the polarity of the off-response matches the on-response because the transducer does not discriminate the direction of pressure application despite the rotational change in pressure distribution. Appendices provide detailed mathematical derivations for the compliance of simply supported cylindrical membranes and the viscous fluid resistance to flow between two cylindrical membranes validating the assumptions regarding laminar flow and negligible inertial effects through Reynolds number checks ultimately establishing that the mechanical transmission properties of the lamellated capsule alone can account for the process of adaptation of the generator response the velocity dependence of the transducer and the existence of the off-response providing a unified theoretical framework linking structural mechanics to electrophysiological output in mechanoreceptors.}
}

@article{mountcastleNeuralBasisSense1967,
  title = {Neural Basis of the Sense of Flutter-Vibration},
  author = {Mountcastle, Vernon B. and Talbot, William H. and Darian-Smith, Ian and Kornhuber\dag, Hans H.},
  date = {1967-02-03},
  journaltitle = {Science},
  shortjournal = {Science},
  doi = {10.1126/science.155.3762.597},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: The study concerning the sedimentation of a gut-factor from roach viscera utilized differential centrifugation of homogenates to determine the physical properties of an active neuromuscular transmitter, finding that complete sedimentation of the light fraction required centrifugal forces exceeding 720,000 g-min while the active factor dissociated from particulate fractions under hypotonic conditions without appearing in the soluble fraction, suggesting enzymatic inactivation rather than mere solubility shifts. Quantitative recovery of the factor was achieved exclusively with extraction media causing enzyme denaturation, such as acidic ethanol or trichloroacetic acid, indicating the presence of a degrading enzyme analogous to those in the cholinergic system, and leading to the proposal that this factor functions as an excitatory transmitter in the longitudinal muscles of the proctodeum. In a concurrent investigation within the same publication, another study explored the neural basis of the sense of flutter-vibration by correlating human detection thresholds for skin oscillation with electrophysiological responses of first-order myelinated mechanoreceptive afferents in monkeys, establishing that this sensory modality is a dual form of mechanical sensibility served peripherally by two distinct sets of fibers. The experimental design combined psychophysical measurements of human perception thresholds with neurophysiological recordings of nerve impulses obtained via microdissection from the median nerve of anesthetized monkeys, aiming to elucidate central mechanisms by linking subjective experience to neural encoding parameters such as dynamic range and information preservation. Results indicated that the perception of oscillatory movement requires a periodic signal within the input impulse trains occurring with probabilities between 0.7 and 0.9, and that frequency discrimination relies on a central mechanism measuring period length rather than specific fiber activation or total impulse counts. Analysis of human threshold curves revealed a bifurcation at approximately 40 to 50 cycles per second, where local anesthesia with cocaine iontophoresis elevated low-frequency thresholds significantly more than high-frequency ones, supporting the involvement of two afferent populations innervating skin versus deep tissues respectively. Myelinated afferents terminating in dermal ridges showed limited frequency following capabilities below 10 cycles per second, whereas cutaneous movement detectors exhibited tuning curves that accounted for human sensitivity in the 2 to 40 cycles per second range through one-to-one phase locking, while a third afferent type terminating in deep tissues, likely Pacinian corpuscles, displayed perfect frequency following at optimal ranges of 150 to 250 cycles per second corresponding to the high-frequency limb of the human threshold curve. Table 1 data confirmed that cutaneous movement detectors locked in phase at low frequencies while Pacinian afferents dominated high frequencies, with an overlap region facilitating the transition in subjective sensation from localized flutter to deep vibratory hum as frequency increased beyond 60 cycles per second. Ultimately, the research concluded that the sense of flutter-vibration exhibits a dual nature in both subjective estimation and first-order afferent properties, implying that the periodic signal in nerve impulse trains is preserved through subcortical nuclei and processed centrally to measure interval lengths, providing a comprehensive model for the neural coding of mechanical vibration and highlighting the necessity of updating comparisons between psychophysical and neurophysiological findings to understand central sensory processing.}
}

