@article{quindlenMultiphysicsModelPacinian2016,
  title = {A Multiphysics Model of the Pacinian Corpuscle},
  author = {Quindlen, Julia C. and Stolarski, Henryk K. and Johnson, Matthew D. and Barocas, Victor H.},
  date = {2016},
  journaltitle = {Integrative Biology},
  shortjournal = {Integr. Biol.},
  doi = {10.1039/C6IB00157B},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: This research paper presents a comprehensive multiphysics model of the Pacinian corpuscle (PC), a dermal mechanoreceptor responsible for detecting high-frequency vibrations between 20 and 1000 Hz, by integrating mechanical models of the PC structure with an electrochemical model of peripheral nerves to simulate the tactile response of the entire system. The study develops a three-stage model comprising outer core mechanics, inner core mechanics, and neurite electrochemistry, which correctly predicts the band-pass nature of the PC's frequency response and demonstrates that the PC structure actively amplifies oscillatory strains within its target frequency band by a factor of 8--12 from the surface to the centrally-located neurite. Beyond the abstract, the introduction establishes the context of the somatosensory system, detailing how cutaneous mechanoreceptors distinguish mechanical stimuli and reviewing the historical progression from functional black-box models to mechanistic physical models of the PC, noting that while previous models have offered insights, detailed filtering mechanisms and adaptation processes remain areas for further investigation. Consequently, this work aims to unify these observations through a detailed mechanistic model that accounts for the fine morphology of the neurite and the three-dimensionality of the PC, serving as a foundation for understanding vibrotactile perception and designing haptic feedback systems. The methodology describes a three-stage computational approach where Stage 1 utilizes a MATLAB-based finite-element mechanical model of the outer core consisting of concentric spherical shells separated by lubricating fluid layers to model fluid-solid interaction and mechanical transmission, employing classical shell theory and lubrication approximations under assumptions of negligible inertia and small displacements. Stage 2 employs a COMSOL finite element platform to simulate the inner core and neurite mechanics, modeling the neurite as an isotropic linearly elastic material with specific geometric features including five filopodia, while applying boundary conditions derived from Stage 1 outputs and measuring principal strains at the filopodial bases. Stage 3 constructs an electrochemical neurite model in NEURON, creating a topological representation of the neurite regions including filopodia, soma, and spike-initiation zones, inserting Hodgkin-Huxley channels, and approximating stretch-gated cation channel opening via injected currents proportional to strains measured at filopodial bases from Stage 2 simulations. The results section reports that frequency sweeps across the three stages confirmed the PC acts as a band-pass filter with peak sensitivity around 150 Hz, revealing that the layered structure amplifies strain significantly more than a homogeneous structure, with radial stretch increasing with proximity to the inner core in Stage 1 and further amplification occurring from the inner core to the neurite filopodia in Stage 2, resulting in a total amplification factor of 8--12. Simulations of sustained pressure demonstrated mechanical adaptation where the inner core was displaced only during the onset and offset of the square wave stimulus, leading to action potentials occurring only at these transitions and reproducing the rapid adaptation seen in biological literature without requiring neuronal adaptivity. Additionally, varying the PC size by altering the number of lamellar layers showed that larger PCs exhibited increased amplification factors and shifted peak frequencies, suggesting that heterogeneous clusters of PCs could encode more amplitude and frequency information than uniform clusters. The discussion highlights the comprehensive nature of the model which combines specific components of the transduction process to simulate the transformation of mechanical input into neural output while accounting for PC core structure and neurite morphology, distinguishing this work from previous cylindrical models by focusing on three-dimensional structure. The authors elucidate three mechanical regimes based on stimulation frequency relative to viscosity and layer count, explaining how fluid viscosity transmits pressure between adjacent shells causing phase shifts in the middle frequency regime, and quantify strain amplification to explain how millimeter-scale PCs detect nanometer-range vibrations. While the model confirms rapid adaptation via mechanical properties consistent with decapsulated PC behavior, it acknowledges potential mechanochemical processes involving neurotransmitters like GABA or ion channels such as ASICs that were not fully captured, and notes limitations including the deterministic nature of the model, the use of squid axon parameters for neural conductance, and the lack of stochastic variations. Finally, the conclusions reiterate that the three-stage model provides insight into how mechanical properties, outer core structure, three-dimensional neurite morphology, and mechanogated channel activation collectively influence mechano-to-neural transduction in the PC, allowing for the characterization of mechanosensation in other receptors and exploring how multiple receptors interact to create the sensation of touch, laying the groundwork for future designs in haptic feedback systems and neural prosthetics.}
}

@article{rakkolainenSurveyMidAirUltrasound2021,
  title = {A {{Survey}} of {{Mid-Air Ultrasound Haptics}} and {{Its Applications}}},
  author = {Rakkolainen, Ismo and Freeman, Euan and Sand, Antti and Raisamo, Roope and Brewster, Stephen},
  date = {2021-01-01},
  journaltitle = {IEEE Transactions on Haptics},
  shortjournal = {IEEE Trans. Haptics},
  doi = {10.1109/TOH.2020.3018754},
  langid = {english},
  note = {Paper Summary: This survey paper presents a comprehensive overview of mid-air ultrasound haptics, a contactless technology enabling rich multisensory feedback through precisely focused sound waves, aiming to address the gap in literature regarding this rapidly advancing field. The introduction establishes the context of haptic devices enhancing human-computer interaction by recreating physical sensations without requiring direct contact, thereby improving immersion in mid-air user interfaces where implicit tactile cues are typically absent and usability challenges persist. While various contactless technologies exist, including air streams, vortex rings, lasers, and electromagnetic fields, ultrasound haptics is distinguished by its ability to create multiple stimulation points with high spatial and temporal resolution across a large workspace without mechanical constraints. The fundamental operation relies on phased ultrasound arrays where independent phase control of dozens or hundreds of emitters causes constructive interference at specific focal points, generating acoustic radiation pressure upon skin contact, with early research transitioning from perpendicular movement to three-dimensional dynamic phase control. To make these ultrasonic pressures perceptible since humans cannot feel ultrasonic frequencies directly, researchers employ modulation techniques such as amplitude modulation, lateral modulation, or spatiotemporal modulation, which convert static pressure into perceived vibrations by stimulating mechanoreceptors like Pacinian corpuscles predominantly found in glabrous skin, with amplitude modulation reducing power output while lateral and spatiotemporal methods maintain full power for stronger sensations. Rendering techniques utilize these focal points to create sensations of motion, volumetric shapes, textured surfaces, and abstract patterns, utilizing sequential points or continuous trajectories, although challenges remain in accurately conveying fine-grained textures due to the relatively large wavelength of 40 kHz ultrasound which limits spatial resolution compared to human tactile acuity. Perceptual studies have investigated parameters for localization, discrimination, and intensity scaling, establishing guidelines for continuous sensations and shape identification, while also exploring illusions of stiffness and force despite the lack of actual resistive force capability. Interaction techniques leverage these capabilities to implement mid-air user interface components like buttons and sliders providing binary or graded feedback, provide guidance for gesture interactions to optimize hand positioning, and render virtual objects in augmented and virtual reality environments to enhance spatial congruence and immersion. Application domains explored include sterile medical interfaces for pulse simulation and palpation training to maintain hygiene, automotive systems offering eyes-free feedback to reduce distraction and improve safety, digital advertising to increase user engagement through novel tactile experiences, and mixed reality experiences combining visual and tactile modalities for entertainment, education, and productivity tools. Despite its potential, the technology faces significant limitations including precision constraints due to grating lobes and wavelength, low tactile force output compared to mechanical actuators which limits kinesthetic force, limited operational range due to signal attenuation typically restricting effective perception to less than fifty centimeters, physiological restrictions to specific skin types like the palm, and substantial size, weight, and power consumption requirements hindering portability. Safety concerns regarding high sound pressure levels are mitigated by the highly localized nature of the focal points, though occupational exposure standards remain a consideration requiring adherence to decibel limits to prevent hearing loss or heating effects. The conclusion emphasizes the need for further research into perceptual understanding, advanced rendering methods capable of simulating material properties beyond simple shapes, and closed-loop systems to improve feedback quality, while highlighting emerging opportunities in hygiene-sensitive sectors like retail following global health crises and suggesting that while nascent, the technology holds significant promise for future HCI developments.}
}

@inproceedings{reardonCutaneousWavePropagation2019,
  title = {Cutaneous Wave Propagation Shapes Tactile Motion: {{Evidence}} from Air-Coupled Ultrasound},
  shorttitle = {Cutaneous Wave Propagation Shapes Tactile Motion},
  booktitle = {2019 {{IEEE World Haptics Conference}} ({{WHC}})},
  author = {Reardon, Gregory and Shao, Yitian and Dandu, Bharat and Frier, William and Long, Ben and Georgiou, Orestis and Visell, Yon},
  date = {2019-07},
  publisher = {IEEE},
  location = {Tokyo, Japan},
  doi = {10.1109/WHC.2019.8816150},
  eventtitle = {2019 {{IEEE World Haptics Conference}} ({{WHC}})},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: This research paper investigates the relationship between cutaneous wave propagation and tactile motion perception using air-coupled ultrasound, presenting evidence that mechanical waves excited in the skin significantly shape the perception of tactile motion cues. The study begins by establishing that tactile stimulation generates mechanical waves traveling tens of centimeters which carry information about tactile events, yet the implications for haptic engineering remain poorly understood due to a lack of direct observation of complex spatiotemporal responses excited by air-coupled ultrasound. Consequently, the authors utilized time-resolved optical vibrometry to measure cutaneous wave fields elicited by focused ultrasound, distinguishing two physical regimes based on the ratio of motion speed to cutaneous wave speed. In the first experiment, skin vibrations on the volar hand surface were captured using a scanning laser doppler vibrometer sampling at 125 kHz while a 16x16 ultrasound phased array delivered tactile motion cues along digit 2 at speeds ranging from 1 to 15 m/s across a 10 cm path with spatiotemporal modulation. The results revealed that at low speeds below 4 m/s, waves propagated outward in all directions to distances exceeding ten centimeters, whereas at high speeds between 4 and 15 m/s, waves in the direction of motion were compressed near the focus, suggesting a Doppler effect consistent with wave mechanics, while waves traveling opposite the motion extended further, with amplitudes varying by local skin geometry. To assess the perceptual relevance of these physical observations, a second behavioral experiment was conducted with twelve participants who performed a two-alternative forced choice task to judge the direction of tactile motion along proximal-distal axes and rightward-leftward axes that crossed disconnected skin regions over 240 trials per participant. The findings indicated that motion discrimination accuracy decreased monotonically with increasing speed, converging to chance levels at approximately 7 m/s for the continuous skin path and 4 m/s for the disconnected path, demonstrating that tactile motion perception is impaired when wave propagation ahead of the moving stimulus is inhibited either by high speed compression or anatomical discontinuities, with Generalized Linear Mixed Models confirming significant interactions between speed and motion axis. The discussion synthesizes these findings to argue that cutaneous waves preceding the stimulus contribute to motion perception, offering the simplest explanation for the observed impairments despite potential confounding factors such as Pacinian afferent integration or anatomical variations, while noting that rightward-leftward motion showed greater asymmetry and lower baseline performance than distal-proximal motion. Finally, the conclusions emphasize that this work provides the first time-resolved observations of cutaneous responses to focused ultrasound, identifying distinct low and high-speed regimes that inform the design of tactile motion and mid-air haptic feedback systems, while noting that future research is needed to clarify the physics of ultrasound-skin coupling and confirm causal relationships between wave patterns and neural processing within virtual and augmented reality applications.}
}

@article{reardonShearShockWaves2023,
  title = {Shear Shock Waves Mediate Haptic Holography via Focused Ultrasound},
  author = {Reardon, Gregory and Dandu, Bharat and Shao, Yitian and Visell, Yon},
  date = {2023-03-03},
  journaltitle = {Science Advances},
  shortjournal = {Sci. Adv.},
  doi = {10.1126/sciadv.adf2037},
  langid = {english},
  note = {Paper Summary: This study investigates the mechanisms underlying the spatial resolution and dynamic range limitations of holographic haptic displays that use focused ultrasound to create tactile sensations in midair. Current systems produce diffuse and faint tactile feedback despite the fine acoustic focusing capabilities of ultrasound, with perceptual acuity far below theoretical predictions. The research demonstrates that ultrasound-driven elastic wave transport in soft tissues, particularly the formation of shear shock waves, significantly impacts the effective resolution of haptic feedback. Through numerical simulations, time-resolved optical imaging, and vibrometry experiments on both tissue phantoms and human hands, the authors show that rapidly scanning ultrasound focal points at transonic or supersonic speeds (relative to shear wave propagation speeds in skin) generates large-amplitude shear shock waves with spatial dimensions exceeding the acoustic focal area by more than an order of magnitude. These shock waves form Mach cones that trail the focal point, distributing energy over large surface areas (10--50 cm{$^2$}) compared to the focal area (0.28--0.36 cm{$^2$}), thereby reducing spatial resolution. Behavioral experiments revealed that perceptual accuracy declines monotonically with increasing wake length, dropping to chance levels at supersonic scanning speeds where shock waves are most pronounced. The study identifies that complex interference patterns arise when scanning trajectories change direction or display closed shapes, creating artifacts that further degrade haptic feedback quality. These findings provide a mechanistic explanation for the diffuse tactile sensations reported by users of current holographic haptic systems and suggest that techniques to mitigate or exploit shear shock phenomena are needed to improve the fidelity of midair haptic displays. The research highlights the critical role of viscoelastic wave transport in determining the perceptual characteristics of ultrasound-based haptic feedback and has important implications for the development of more effective holographic interfaces for virtual reality, teleoperation, and other applications.}
}

@article{saalSimulatingTactileSignals2017,
  ids = {saalSimulatingTactileSignals2017a},
  title = {Simulating Tactile Signals from the Whole Hand with Millisecond Precision},
  author = {Saal, Hannes P. and Delhaye, Benoit P. and Rayhaun, Brandon C. and Bensmaia, Sliman J.},
  date = {2017-07-11},
  journaltitle = {Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences},
  shortjournal = {Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A.},
  doi = {10.1073/pnas.1704856114},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: This study by Saal et al. addresses the primitive state of understanding regarding population-level representations in tactile neuroscience despite extensive characterization of single-unit response properties. To bridge this gap, the authors developed a comprehensive computational model capable of simulating the responses of all tactile nerve fibers innervating the glabrous skin of the hand to any applied spatiotemporal stimulus with millisecond precision. The model operates through a two-stage mechanotransduction process wherein skin deformations are reconstructed using continuum mechanics to estimate stresses comprising a quasistatic component related to pressure redistribution and a dynamic component resulting from propagating surface waves; these mechanical inputs subsequently drive leaky integrate-and-fire spiking models fitted individually to afferent data, incorporating up to thirteen free parameters per fiber to account for heterogeneity within afferent classes. Validated against neurophysiological datasets from rhesus macaques and humans using sinusoidal, bandpass noise, and diharmonic vibrations, the model demonstrates high fidelity, matching measured firing rates with R-squared values exceeding 0.90 and achieving temporal precision better than 8 milliseconds, with Pacinian models reaching submillisecond accuracy, utilizing a van Rossum spike distance metric optimized via genetic algorithms to ensure accurate prediction without overfitting. Systematic comparisons confirm the model captures canonical biological properties including adaptation to ramp-and-hold indentations, hierarchical receptive field sizes where slowly adapting type I fibers possess the smallest fields and Pacinian fibers the largest, distinct frequency sensitivity profiles across afferent classes, and spatial interaction phenomena such as edge enhancement and surround suppression. Beyond single-unit validation, the researchers utilized the model to simulate entire populations of approximately 12,500 afferents distributed according to known innervation densities wherein RA fibers outnumber SA1 fibers by a factor of two and SA1 fibers outnumber PC fibers by a factor of two, revealing that most tactile experiences recruit multiple fiber populations simultaneously with spike counts varying over orders of magnitude depending on stimulus dynamics. Virtual experiments further elucidated population coding principles by simulating edge indentations at 32 orientations and texture scanning in 16 directions, demonstrating that edge orientation can be decoded from population spike counts within tens of milliseconds, largely relying on spatial activation patterns rather than precise spike timing, whereas decoding motion direction benefits significantly from analyzing correlated activity across adjacent neuron pairs using cross-correlograms. These findings suggest a cooperative interplay between submodalities where combined signals from different afferent populations provide more informative representations than any single group, challenging historical assumptions about specialized encoding channels. While acknowledging limitations such as the exclusion of slowly adapting type II fibers, the approximation of lateral sliding as frame-by-frame indentation, and the assumption of flat skin mechanics ignoring three-dimensional bulging, the authors argue the framework remains robust for investigating peripheral neural codes and psychophysical correlations. Finally, the paper highlights critical applications in neuroprosthetics, proposing that the model can convert outputs from prosthetic touch sensors into biomimetic afferent responses to drive electrical stimulation in residual nerves, thereby restoring naturalistic artificial touch, and underscores the model's computational efficiency which allows for real-time simulation essential for both basic somatosensory research and clinical interface development.}
}

@article{sandrinTimeresolvedPulsedElastography1999,
  title = {Time-Resolved Pulsed Elastography with Ultrafast Ultrasonic Imaging},
  author = {Sandrin, L and Catheline, S. and Tanter, M. and Hennequin, X. and Fink, M.},
  date = {1999-10},
  journaltitle = {Ultrasonic Imaging},
  shortjournal = {Ultrason Imaging},
  doi = {10.1177/016173469902100402},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: The paper proposes a novel elastographic method designed to image the propagation of a low-frequency transient shear wave using a newly developed ultrafast ultrasonic imaging system capable of achieving frame rates up to 10,000 frames per second. This system utilizes a linear array of transducers operating at 3.5 MHz connected to electronics featuring 64 channels sampled at 30 MHz with 128 Kbytes of memory per channel to store backscattered signals, while tissue displacements are measured through the cross-correlation of ultrasonic signals to produce movies of shear wave propagation at 1,000 to 2,000 frames per second. Relative stiffness imaging is highlighted as critical because pathological states in soft tissues correlate with stiffness changes, although traditional palpation fails for deep or small lesions and echogenicity generally does not correlate with stiffness. Various methods have emerged including quasistatic compression elastography and time-dependent excitation techniques such as sonoelasticity which stimulate tissue with monochromatic mechanical excitation and measure motion using color Doppler instruments. Recent studies by Parker et al. and Sato et al. investigated lesion detectability in vibration sonoelastography and applied pulse Doppler techniques to detect inner tissue displacement, while Greenleaf et al. studied shear wave propagation in phantoms and muscles estimating local displacements via phase of quadrature echo signals compared against magnetic resonance imaging. Catheline et al. described biases induced by diffraction in sonoelastography when shear waves are generated by forced monochromatic vibration, showing that apparent shear wave velocity depends on frequency and proposing transient elastography to separate compressional and shear waves using transient excitation. This transient elastography method avoids diffraction biases and allows measurement of both shear elasticity and viscosity by observing the fast compressional wave followed by the slow shear wave. The present work expands upon Catheline et al.'s transient elastography by studying two-dimensional shear wave propagation using an ultrafast ultrasonic imaging electronic system that reduces acquisition times considerably compared with MRI or Doppler techniques. The experimental setup involves a circular piston built on a vibrator vibrating perpendicularly to the medium surface, controlled by a function generator and operated with a personal computer. Standard ultrasonic scanners are limited to about 100 frames per second which is insufficient to follow the evolution of displacements induced by low-frequency shear waves that propagate at a few meters per second on a millimeter scale. Ultrafast imaging is obtained by avoiding focusing in transmit and during reception, instead performing parallel beam forming numerically afterwards so that the frame rate is limited only by the ultrasound travel time of 100 microseconds in a 7.5 cm deep medium, physically limiting the rate to 10,000 frames per second. The medium is illuminated with a plane wave and each element of the 64-element linear array stores backscattered signals in its own memory to construct speckle images via parallel beam forming which consists of delaying and adding responses from different elements relative to image positions. The calculation of the time delay law is discretized over depth at locations corresponding to focal zones to maintain a constant f-number over maximum depth, though lateral resolution diminishes as distance increases. High dynamic range is not required for the cross-correlation analysis which is sensitive to phase rather than amplitude, and the parallel beam forming is performed on a PC taking typically 2 minutes to treat the content of the entire channel memories. Axial displacement is estimated in 2 mm slices using the cross-correlation technique between successive speckle images with a precision of about 1 micrometer, deriving N displacement images from N speckle data sets. Experiments were conducted in tissue-mimicking heterogeneous and homogeneous gel-based phantoms containing agar powder for echogenicity with stiffness contrast obtained using different gelatin concentrations between 3 and 10 percent. The excitation central frequency was 200 Hz with an amplitude of about 1 mm, lasting 3 periods for the homogeneous phantom and 1 period for heterogeneous phantoms, with acquisition times of about 50 ms and post-acquisition procedures taking about 5 minutes. Phantom configurations varied with the piston and transducer array placed face-to-face for homogeneous and inclusion phantoms while side-by-side for bilayered phantoms to accommodate symmetry expectations. In the homogeneous phantom axial displacements were represented every 3 ms showing a transient shear wave speed estimated at about 2 meters per second with displacement amplitude attenuating as the wave propagated deeper. The wavelength was about 1 cm and the shear modulus approximately 4,000 Pa, with a nonzero longitudinal displacement due to the shear wave observed on the vibrator axis close to the source but disappearing in the far field. For the bilayered phantom a framerate of 1,000 frames per second was used yielding forty-two displacement images measured with 1 micrometer precision showing images antisymmetric with respect to the vibrator axis. The wavelength decreased from 2 cm in the hard layer to 1 cm in the soft medium while wave speed decreased from 4 m/s in the hard layer to 2 m/s in the soft layer resulting in shear moduli of 16 kPa and 4 kPa respectively. Refraction was observed at the interface between the two layers where the wave front rotated as the wave penetrated into the soft layer. The phantom with a cylindrical inclusion was imaged at 2,000 frames per second obtaining seventy-four frames and seventy-three displacement images with images symmetric with respect to the vibrator axis showing shear moduli of 36 kPa in the hard region and 9 kPa in the soft region. In both heterogeneous cases the shear wave behavior was modified by the presence of heterogeneities despite different displacement amplitudes in hard and soft regions, allowing qualitative estimates of shear modulus to be obtained. Watching displacement images animation versus time gave a clear indication of the presence of heterogeneities. The important result presented is the possibility of imaging the propagation of a transient low frequency shear wave in biological tissues by means of an ultrafast ultrasonic imaging system capable of producing up to 10,000 frames per second. Shear wave propagation images were obtained with 1,000 and 2,000 frames per second from homogeneous and heterogeneous phantoms allowing the wavelength and speed of the shear wave to be qualitatively estimated and the shear modulus to be obtained. Since displacements induced by the propagating centimeter wavelength shear wave are measured locally inside the medium, the resolution of this imaging technique is expected to be the same as that of the image of the displacements. Future plans include measuring lateral displacements to solve the inverse problem and recover the stiffness distribution in the tissue using two components of the displacement vector.}
}

@incollection{suzukiMidairUltrasoundHaptic2019,
  title = {Midair {{Ultrasound Haptic Display}} with {{Large Workspace}}},
  booktitle = {Haptic {{Interaction}}},
  author = {Suzuki, Shun and Fujiwara, Masahiro and Makino, Yasutoshi and Shinoda, Hiroyuki},
  editor = {Kajimoto, Hiroyuki and Lee, Dongjun and Kim, Sang-Youn and Konyo, Masashi and Kyung, Ki-Uk},
  date = {2019},
  publisher = {Springer Singapore},
  location = {Singapore},
  doi = {10.1007/978-981-13-3194-7_1},
  langid = {english},
  note = {Paper Summary: This research paper presents a midair ultrasound haptic display system designed to overcome the workspace limitations of conventional systems by integrating multiple ultrasound display units to create a large workspace of approximately 2 cubic meters, enabling visuo-tactile interaction with augmented reality images without requiring users to wear any devices. The introduction outlines the background of airborne ultrasound tactile displays, highlighting their non-contact haptic feedback capabilities and advantages in virtual, augmented, and mixed reality environments, while noting that previous systems like HaptoMime and HaptoClone were confined to a 30 cm cube workspace due to ultrasound attenuation in air, necessitating many transducers for effective convergence, which the authors address by using multiple phased array units for flexible large workspace design. The prototype system configuration involves multiple AUTD units, each equipped with a depth sensor for 3D measurement, a slave PC, and nine AUTD subunits, all synchronized via LAN to transmit point cloud data to a master PC that controls the units based on sensor data. Each AUTD unit features nine subunits with 249 ultrasonic transducers each, totaling 2241 transducers per unit, fixed to an aluminum frame alongside a depth sensor, with pre-measured positional relationships between subunits and sensors for accuracy. Stereoscopic 3D images are rendered using a mixed reality device like HoloLens, calibrated once with AUTD units via a calibration pattern, leveraging the device's self-position estimation for multiple unit calibrations. The conclusion emphasizes the system's achievement of a large workspace allowing standing users to move hands freely and interact with 3D images via tactile feedback, though objective evaluation of midair haptics in such a space remains for future study.}
}

@article{takahashiTactileStimulationRepetitive2020,
  title = {Tactile Stimulation by Repetitive Lateral Movement of Midair Ultrasound Focus},
  author = {Takahashi, Ryoko and Hasegawa, Keisuke and Shinoda, Hiroyuki},
  date = {2020-04-01},
  journaltitle = {IEEE Transactions on Haptics},
  shortjournal = {IEEE Trans. Haptics},
  doi = {10.1109/TOH.2019.2946136},
  langid = {american},
  note = {Paper Summary: The authors report a novel vibrotactile modulation method for midair ultrasound focus termed lateral modulation (LM), wherein the focus moves along a small cyclic trajectory to deliver stronger and clearer stimuli compared to conventional amplitude modulation (AM). Midair ultrasound haptics offers remote, non-contact, pinpoint tactile stimuli on bare skin, yet clarity issues and limitations to glabrous skin have persisted. The study verifies LM, confirming that with identical maximum output amplitude, LM stimuli with circular focal trajectories are sensed more strongly than AM stimuli by both glabrous and hairy skin across modulation frequencies of 10-200 Hz. Furthermore, detection thresholds in glabrous skin primarily depend on focal speed, whereas hairy skin exhibits different tendencies, prompting a discussion on the perceptual mechanisms underlying LM stimuli response alongside practical application aspects. Acoustic radiation pressure generated by a midair ultrasound focus produces non-contact tactile stimuli on bare skin, a principle established since the first demonstration and subsequently developed into phased array systems like the airborne ultrasound tactile display (AUTD). Applications have diversified to include midair visuo-tactile interaction systems where aerial tactile feedback is superimposed on floating images, such as aerial touch panels and visual-tactile clone systems, highlighting the essential advantage of midair ultrasound haptics in instantaneously presenting localized tactile sensations at arbitrary positions. The greatest radiation pressure is attained by generating an ultrasound focus, and intensifying stimulation involves providing time-variant stimuli to exploit human touch perception mechanisms where mechanoreceptors respond selectively to temporal characteristics. While amplitude modulation (AM) of the output waveform is prevalent, utilizing waveforms with frequency components above 100 Hz for glabrous skin, successful presentation remains limited to glabrous skin as hairy skin requires strong user attention or voluntary movements for perceivable sensation. Although increasing transducer count improves focal intensity, it raises power consumption and device costs, leading to the proposal of lateral modulation (LM) which maintains constant ultrasound intensity while varying the focal position over a short trajectory perceived as directionless point vibrotactile stimulation. The study aims to verify LM effectiveness on both skin types with varied experimental parameters and discuss the detailed conditions and mechanism, noting that unlike active applications targeting palms, this method facilitates perceivable stimuli on wider body regions for passive contents like tactile triggers during voluntary movements. A primary characteristic of midair ultrasound haptics is the generation of radiation pressure perpendicular to the skin surface without shear force, rendering reports on shear-force-dependent perception inapplicable, while frequency factors remain influential on perceptual intensity. For the LM method, repetitive focal movement causes mechanical vibration on individual mechanoreceptors with acoustic power effectively doubled compared to AM, yet threshold decreases cannot be explained solely by power increase, indicating that the movement of the stimulation point inherently increases subjective intensity. Additional experiments clarified factors affecting tactile perception, revealing that glabrous skin sensitivity mainly depended on focal speed with detection thresholds declining as speed increased below 2 m/s, a tendency not observed in hairy skin, suggesting the LM focus might selectively stimulate specific mechanoreceptor types. An AUTD comprises ultrasound transducers arranged in a lattice pattern with individually controllable phase and amplitude, concentrating acoustic power in a circular region called a focus depending on focal depth and emission aperture width. Focusing is achieved when each transducer emits ultrasound with determined phase delays so outputs are in phase at the focal position, generating positive acoustic radiation pressure on solid objects blocking propagation to offer non-contact tactile sensations. Generating infallibly detectable vibrotactile sensation necessitates time-variant stimuli to mechanoreceptors, leading to the widespread use of temporal amplitude modulation of ultrasound pressure in midair haptics. The AM envelope of the carrier sinusoidal waveform corresponds to the vibrotactile stimulation waveform, typically using a 40 kHz carrier frequency much higher than the upper limit of perceivable vibrotactile frequency, with driving signals provided by digital FPGA outputs tuning amplitudes via duty cycle similar to pulse-width modulation. While appropriately tuned waveforms offer particular textures, sinusoidal modulations were used in experiments, noting that vibration detection thresholds on glabrous skin are lowest around 200 Hz presumably due to Pacinian corpuscle response, though perceiving stimuli on hairy skin with AM is difficult especially when modulation frequency exceeds 200 Hz. The proposed LM method presents vibrotactile stimuli by a focus repetitively traveling along a horizontal trajectory while keeping radiation pressure intensity constant, defining two specific methods based on focal trajectories: periodic linear movement (LML) and periodic circular motion (LMC). Parameters are defined including LM center, amplitude, frequency, and focal movement speed calculated as the product of amplitude and frequency, with LM applying twice the acoustic power to the entire skin in time average compared to AM for identical maximum presented pressure. Instantaneous acoustic pressures differ between AM and LM formulations, resulting in LM power being double AM power, considering LM frequency, amplitude, and orbit as independent factors affecting subjective intensity. Focal movement speed varies sinusoidally with LML but remains stationary with LMC regarding absolute value calculations, and acoustic field measurements around the ultrasonic focus reveal spot sizes comparable to the wavelength with potential harmonic distortions in the vibration waveform. The experimental workspace consisted of four AUTD units mounted on a ceiling aluminum frame with a total of 996 transducers covering a 384x302.8 mm{$^2$} emission plane, operating at a 200 mm distance from the target. Participants configured focal depth interactively to compensate for anatomical differences, wore headphones playing white noise to cancel auditory clues, and rested their hands or forearms on cushions to fix stimulation positions and insulate from device vibration. Six male and four female subjects aged 22-25 years participated, with forearms and palms stimulated as representative hairy and glabrous parts respectively, and ethical approval was obtained from the University of Tokyo committee. The first experiment measured acoustic pressure waveforms generated by the LM method using an electret condenser microphone on a fixed position connected to an oscilloscope. Radiation pressure was processed with a low-pass filter to remove the carrier signal, measuring waveforms at four points located on three focal orbits: stationary sinusoidal AM focus, center of LML orbit, endpoint of LML orbit, and a point on the LMC orbit with modulation frequency set to 25 Hz and LM amplitude to 7 mm to evaluate harmonic magnitudes. In this subjective evaluation experiment, participants evaluated the difference between AM and LMC stimuli by impressions, presenting them sequentially in random order at maximum intensity on the hairy part of the forearm with a 50 Hz modulation frequency. After presentation, ten participants were asked which stimulus was stronger without permitting equivocal answers, aiming to confirm LMC is felt as stronger than AM at maximum intensity. This experiment obtained the vibrotactile detection threshold of AM and LMC stimuli on glabrous and hairy skin regarding modulation frequencies and LM amplitudes, stimulating the left palm and left forearm center. The procedure involved initial static pressure presentation equal to the time-average to subtract offset effects, followed by vibrotactile stimulus initiation with a cue sound where participants responded to felt vibrations. Stimulus intensity was defined by maximum instantaneous output radiation pressure altered among 51 levels, obtaining detection thresholds via the method of limits with modulation frequencies of 10, 50, 100, and 200 Hz and LM amplitudes of 1, 3, 5, and 7 mm excluding 1 mm for hairy skin due to non-perception at maximum output. As Experiment 3 indicated perceptual intensity dependence on LMC parameters, further experiments investigated whether this tendency depended on focal trajectories by conducting trials with LML stimuli on the palm using the same participants and similar procedures. The LM frequency was set to 10, 50, 100, and 200 Hz, and the LM amplitude was set to 1, 3, 5, and 7 mm to compare thresholds against the previous findings. Figure 7 displays waveforms measured by the ECM showing a common fundamental frequency of 25 Hz with a second harmonic observed prominently at the center point of LML, consistent with expectations that the doubled frequency effect is dominant only in the case of LML. In this experiment, all participants answered that LMC was stronger, serving as a confirmation that LMC stimuli are infallibly felt as stronger than AM when both are at maximum intensity. On glabrous skin, LMC data sets mostly followed normal distribution, with the maximum difference in detection threshold between AM and LMC being 20.2 dB for 50 Hz 7 mm stimuli, and thresholds for 3, 5, and 7 mm LMC stimuli significantly different from AM across all frequencies. Two-way repeated measures ANOVA found both LM amplitude and frequency significantly affected the threshold, lowering it as they increased, consistent with Pacinian corpuscle response characteristics. One-way ANOVA with focal speed as a factor rejected the null hypothesis, showing thresholds monotonically lowered with speed increase until around 2 m/s, indicating focal speed is a more definitive factor than amplitude or frequency alone, while stimulation area size was less definitive due to remaining frequency influence. On hairy skin, cases where vibration was not felt at maximum output were counted as 0 dB thresholds, with AM stimuli at various frequencies often undetectable by multiple participants. The maximum difference in detection threshold between AM and LMC was 10.8 dB for 50 Hz 7 mm stimuli, with all LMC thresholds significantly different from AM of the same frequency. Two-way ANOVA found neither LM frequency nor amplitude had significant influence on threshold, and one-way ANOVA with focal speed did not reject the null hypothesis that mean threshold is irrespective of focal speed, showing thresholds were irrespective of these factors unlike glabrous skin results. Figure 14 shows LML and LMC stimuli plotted against focal movement speed, where speeds ranged from 0.04 to 5.6 m/s. Regardless of focal movement pattern, thresholds tended to lie on a single line decreasing monotonically for speeds less than 2 m/s, with LML and LMC threshold distributions roughly overlapping, while at faster speeds, the increase in focal movement speed became less influential in the threshold. Shapiro-Wilk test confirmed normal distribution for LML data, and one-way ANOVA demonstrated LML focal speed significantly affected the threshold, noting similar focal-speed-dependency of detection threshold was observed regardless of focal trajectory shapes despite procedural differences. For both glabrous and hairy skin, lateral modulation was demonstrated to be effective in significantly lowering detection thresholds across a wide range of modulation frequencies compared to conventional AM, an effect not ascribable merely to doubled acoustic power corresponding to a 6 dB difference. Effects of second harmonics in LML were not dominant, concluding that movement of the stimulation point inherently increases sensitivity, making LM advantageous for power consumption. Geometries of focal paths were found less likely to affect thresholds due to similarity between LML and LMC curves, with two possible factors explaining speed-dependence: physical effects on the skin involving surface wave interference maximized around 8 m/s, and physiological possibilities where perceptional mechanisms selectively respond to moving stimuli. Previous studies suggested Meissner corpuscles firing rates correlate with brush speed, indicating spatial movement without shear force promotes receptor firing, leading to the assumption that LM stimuli selectively stimulate Meissner corpuscles sensitive to temporal stress derivatives, while Pacinian corpuscles are insensitive to minute spatial changes. This perception intensity monotonic increase with speed continues until saturation around 2 m/s, a tendency not applied to hairy skin where hair follicles act as mechanoreceptors differing physically and physiologically. Combined with AM expected to mainly stimulate Pacinian corpuscles, there is a possibility of texture creation in midair haptics, and while acoustic streaming accompanies high-intensity fields, its effect was considered insignificant due to validated focal-speed-dependence. The study proposed lateral modulation as a new method to present midair ultrasound vibrotactile stimuli and verified its effectiveness in enhancing subjective strength on both glabrous and hairy skin compared to conventional AM methods valid for 10-200 Hz modulations. Discussions referred to the possibility that each modulation mode may selectively stimulate different types of mechanoreceptors based on experimental results and haptic physiology fundamentals, allowing clear perception on forearms covered by hairy skin. Results would be utilized to develop full-body haptics systems after further investigations of thresholds in other body regions, suggesting facts about stimuli without shear force that moving stimulation speed influences perception intensity significantly. It is important to set moving stimulus speed above 2 m/s to ensure sufficient strength for glabrous skin, with future challenges including designing tactile textures based on LM and AM combinations and implementing passive whole-body haptic systems based on the LM method.}
}

@article{talbotSenseFluttervibrationComparison1968a,
  title = {The Sense of Flutter-Vibration: {{Comparison}} of the Human Capacity with Response Patterns of Mechanoreceptive Afferents from the Monkey Hand.},
  shorttitle = {The Sense of Flutter-Vibration},
  author = {Talbot, W H and Darian-Smith, I and Kornhuber, H H and Mountcastle, V B},
  date = {1968-03},
  journaltitle = {Journal of Neurophysiology},
  shortjournal = {J. Neurophysiol.},
  doi = {10.1152/jn.1968.31.2.301},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: This study by Talbot, Darian-Smith, Kornhuber, and Mountcastle integrates psychophysical and electrophysiological methodologies to investigate the neural mechanisms underlying the human sense of flutter-vibration by comparing behavioral capacities with the response patterns of mechanoreceptive afferents in the monkey hand. The authors posit that correlating these two experimental designs will establish the dynamic range of input required to account for sensory output and determine which neural codes are functionally significant, operating on the assumption that the neurophysiological observations in monkeys can validly correlate with psychophysical measures in humans given a precise identity of experimental design. To achieve this, the researchers utilized a mechanical stimulator controlling the axial movement of Lucite probes to deliver regularly oscillating stimuli consisting of a sinusoidal displacement superimposed on a stepwise indentation of the skin, with parameters held constant across both species including a step rise time of 30 msec, an amplitude of approximately 930 microns, and a sinusoidal duration gated for roughly 930 msec. In the animal experiments, fifty-two median nerve preparations in Macaca mulatta were anesthetized with sodium pentobarbital, and single fibers were isolated via microdissection to record action potentials, while human subjects underwent psychophysical testing where thresholds for recognizing movement and subjective magnitude estimations were determined using iontophoretic cocaine anesthesia to selectively desensitize the dermis. The psychophysical results revealed that the human frequency-intensity threshold function is double-limbed, characterized by a low-frequency range (5-40 cycles/sec) experienced as light flutter localized accurately on the skin surface, and a high-frequency range (60-300 cycles/sec) perceived as a deep vibratory hum less accurately localized. Crucially, local skin anesthesia elevated thresholds in the low-frequency range by factors of 5 to 10 while leaving high-frequency sensitivity largely unaffected, supporting the hypothesis that flutter-vibration is served by two distinct sets of afferent fibers: one innervating the glabrous skin and sensitive to low frequencies, and another terminating in deep tissues sensitive to high frequencies. Electrophysiological analysis identified three classes of large myelinated afferents projecting to the lemniscal system: quickly adapting movement detectors ending in dermal ridges, slowly adapting movement and intensity detectors also in dermal ridges, and Pacinian afferents terminating in subcutaneous corpuscles, with the latter two groups showing distinct conduction velocities and adaptive properties. The quickly adapting cutaneous fibers displayed best tuning frequencies around 30-40 cycles/sec, whereas Pacinian afferents were tuned to approximately 250 cycles/sec, and both classes exhibited a specific dynamic response to sinusoidal stimulation where increasing amplitude first produced demultiplication of discharge, followed by a tuning point where the fiber fired one impulse per cycle in phase-lock, and subsequently entered a tuning plateau where firing rate remained constant despite further increases in stimulus intensity before eventually disorganizing. Comparison of the neural tuning curves with the human threshold function demonstrated that the lower limbs of the tuning curves for the sensitive quickly adapting fibers blanket the low-frequency limb of the human threshold, while the Pacinian afferents account for the high-frequency limb, effectively ruling out slowly adapting afferents as primary contributors due to their entrainment thresholds often exceeding human perceptual limits or requiring specific mismatches between steady-state discharge and stimulus frequency. Despite the neural response plateauing over a wide range of increasing intensities, human subjective magnitude estimation remained a linear function of sine-wave amplitude, presenting a paradox that the authors suggest may be resolved by central spatial integration of activity across the population of neurons engaged by the stimulus rather than by rate coding in the first-order fibers alone. The discussion further elaborates that the perception of regular oscillatory movement depends upon the appearance of periodically periodic trains of nerve impulses in primary afferents, with pitch discrimination likely mediated by a central mechanism measuring the dominant period of input trains rather than shifting populations of active fibers, and notes that the drop in perceived pitch associated with increased intensity correlates with the disorganization of periodic signaling observed in the neural responses. Finally, the study highlights that mechanical impedance of tissue is minimal in the high-frequency range matching Pacinian sensitivity, whereas cutaneous quickly adapting fibers operate in a high-impedance range, implying their tuning is intrinsic to the receptor mechanics, and concludes that the combined data establish the limits and parameters expected of the higher-order neural mechanisms intervening between initial cortical display and sensory experience in the somesthetic sphere.}
}

@article{teeSkininspiredOrganicDigital2015,
  title = {A Skin-Inspired Organic Digital Mechanoreceptor},
  author = {Tee, Benjamin C.-K. and Chortos, Alex and Berndt, Andre and Nguyen, Amanda Kim and Tom, Ariane and McGuire, Allister and Lin, Ziliang Carter and Tien, Kevin and Bae, Won-Gyu and Wang, Huiliang and Mei, Ping and Chou, Ho-Hsiu and Cui, Bianxiao and Deisseroth, Karl and Ng, Tse Nga and Bao, Zhenan},
  date = {2015-10-16},
  journaltitle = {Science},
  shortjournal = {Science},
  doi = {10.1126/science.aaa9306},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: This research paper presents the development of a skin-inspired organic digital mechanoreceptor designed to mimic the function of human cutaneous receptors which output digital signals for tactile sensing by converting stimulation intensity into a series of voltage pulses. The authors describe a power-efficient mechanoreceptor utilizing a flexible organic transistor circuit that directly transduces pressure into digital frequency signals ranging between zero and two hundred hertz, featuring a sublinear response to increasing force stimuli that emulates slow-adapting skin mechanoreceptors. The utility of this system is demonstrated through its ability to stimulate optogenetically engineered mouse somatosensory neurons in vitro, achieving stimulated pulses that correspond accurately with pressure levels, representing a significant step toward large-area organic electronic skins with neural-integrated touch feedback for replacement limbs. Neuraly controlled prosthetic devices significantly improve mobility and independence, and adding tactile sensing enhances motor control and relieves phantom limb pain, making the implementation of human mechanoreceptor-like sensing systems crucial for highly functional prosthetics. While flexible and stretchable tactile sensors have achieved sophistication using organic and inorganic materials, many rely on direct-current amplitude-modulated signals susceptible to drift and noise over long distances, and powering large densities of sensors may not be energy-efficient using such approaches. In contrast, biological tactile mechanoreceptors are sophisticated low-power circuits transducing mechanical strain to oscillating electrical action potentials, which is inherently power-efficient and robust to noise, allowing sensations to be transmitted over long distances. Previous prosthetic skin systems required computers or microcontrollers to convert analog sensor signals into neuron-stimulating signals, whereas this work enables large-scale integration by having sensors directly produce digital signals with relevant frequencies. The presented skin-inspired artificial mechanoreceptor system, termed the Digital Tactile System or DiTact, is composed of flexible organic electronic materials that emulate slow-adapting tactile receptors by encoding static pressure stimuli into digital signals whose frequency varies with stimulation intensity. The digitizing system consists of three key components including voltage-controlled oscillators constructed with printed organic circuits, flexible microstructured resistive pressure sensors with sensitivity in the range of human pressure-sensing capability, and a channelrhodopsin engineered specifically to enable optical neuron stimulation above one hundred hertz. Printed organic circuits are a promising scalable technology for electronic skins due to their potential for low-cost large-area processing and compatibility with flexible substrates, with printed organic ring oscillator circuits consisting of odd numbers of repeating inverter stages based on complementary field-effect transistors used to generate voltage spike series. Complementary ring oscillators are desirable for their simplicity, low static power dissipation, and dependence of oscillation frequency on supply voltage, where a piezoresistive element in a voltage divider modulates time delay so that increased applied force increases supply voltage and reduces propagation delay thereby increasing oscillation frequency. The DiTact prototype utilizes a three-inverter ring oscillator which is the minimum required for stable oscillation, offering advantages of higher-frequency operation, lower power consumption, and smaller device footprints, printed on a flexible plastic sheet with a modified dielectric of high dielectric constant. The system relies on a change in voltage supply to modulate the frequency output of the sensors, with oscillation frequency depending quadratically on supply voltage within the work range, choosing an eleven-volt supply to set the maximum frequency to two hundred hertz to match biological mechanoreceptor ranges, noting that supply voltage can be further reduced via dielectric thickness reduction. To emulate human tactile perception, the DiTact system must exhibit slow or no oscillation absent pressure stimulation with frequency increasing with pressure, requiring the pressure sensor impedance to be larger than the oscillator impedance in the off-state to conserve power by minimizing leakage, yet smaller in the on-state within typical grip control pressures ranging from several to several hundred kilopascals. To create such a wide-impedance piezoresistor, sensors were constructed from a carbon nanotube composite dispersed in a polyurethane elastomer molded into pyramidal microstructures, where the choice of microstructures is essential to achieve desired working range and sensing characteristics. Incorporation of pyramidal structures reduces effective modulus and concentrates the electric field, resulting in improved piezoresistive properties relative to an unstructured film, while size and spacing effects influence sensitivity and working range. Because the function is based on tunneling between carbon nanotubes and an electrode, the devices show substantial voltage dependence in sensing characteristics, with pressure- and voltage-dependent impedance fitted to a mathematical model for circuit characterization. When the sensor and oscillator are in series in a voltage divider, the frequency of the oscillator increases with pressure, with power dissipation of the prototype being favorable compared to analog approaches in the on state. A model hand depicts how sensors could be incorporated into a prosthetic device with electrical components connected with stretchable silver nanowire conductors, and the DiTact sensors were incorporated with a wearable glove to show frequency variation of the voltage signal with the application of pressure in a wearable system. The pressure-induced frequency-encoded digital signal output from the DiTact system was used to directly stimulate mouse cortical neurons both electrically and optically, where although electrical stimulation is more applicable to conventional prosthetics, optogenetic stimulation serves as a promising reliable noncontact method to demonstrate the feasibility of interfacing with biological neural circuits. Optogenetics induces action potentials with excellent fidelity allowing the DiTact signal to be effectively transmitted to target neurons, using the output signal to directly modulate the frequency of an LED light source that evokes neuronal firing in neurons expressing light-activated ion channels such as channelrhodopsin-2. The DiTact sensor was engineered to have a maximum frequency of two hundred hertz comparable to the upper limit for action potential generation during tactile stimulation in humans, requiring the optogenetic neural interface to be capable of stimulating neurons with a frequency up to two hundred hertz for several seconds. Sustained high-frequency stimulation is difficult to achieve using conventional optogenetic channel proteins, and while mutations like ChETA accelerate channel opening and closure, they were found not well suited in cultured pyramidal neurons to mediate spikes for extended periods. Therefore, the researchers engineered the channelrhodopsin hybrid C1C2 because of its larger activity relative to ChR2, resulting in the construct termed bC1C2 with larger photocurrents than ChR2 and ChETA as well as fast off-kinetics. Expression of ChETA and bC1C2 separately in cortical fast-spiking parvalbumin-positive neurons and comparison using whole-cell patch-amp recordings of acute slices confirmed the larger photocurrents and fast kinetics of bC1C2 which was able to reliably evoke action potentials at frequencies up to two hundred hertz for more prolonged intervals mimicking the frequency range of slow-adapting and fast-spiking tactile receptors such as Merkel cells. To interface the digital signal from the DiTact system with live neurons, the sensor output was connected to a setup where the signal was conditioned via an edge detector to a two-millisecond pulse that triggered the LED once per oscillation, using the light pulse to optogenetically stimulate parvalbumin-positive neurons in an acute slice of primary somatosensory cortex from mice. For the sensor composition used in the neuron stimulation study, the frequency exhibited a sublinear dependence on pressure, with neurons firing in accordance with the stimulation pulse generated at frequencies determined by the pressure applied to the DiTact system. The output of the DiTact system had pressure-dependent frequency characteristics with a threshold and range similar to those of biological mechanoreceptors, though the system currently encodes static pressure stimuli and implementing temporal adaptation to both static and nonstatic stimuli would be important to fully mimic biological mechanoreceptor properties. To demonstrate compatibility with electrical stimulation methods, an inorganic oscillator was coupled to the pressure sensor and the resulting frequency signal was successfully used to stimulate hippocampal neurons in a multielectrode array. The compatibility of the DiTact sensor with optogenetic stimulation of somatosensory cortex interneurons and parvalbumin neurons, as well as electrical stimulation of hippocampal neurons, suggests the system would be compatible with other fast-spiking neurons including peripheral nerves. The DiTact sensors encode pressure stimulation magnitude with sublinear digital responses similar to human mechanoreceptors, and the output of the sensors can stimulate in vitro neurons both electrically and optically with engineered optogenetic neurons that respond to the range of human action potential frequencies. This system can be potentially integrated over large areas as electronic skins for conventional neural prosthetics or optogenetic-based prosthetic interfaces, and furthermore the digital nature of the output could be advantageous in high-density prosthetic sensor systems using strategies similar to code division multiple access that allow for greater bandwidths with fewer interconnections.}
}

@article{verrilloEffectContactorArea1963,
  title = {Effect of Contactor Area on the Vibrotactile Threshold},
  author = {Verrillo, Ronald T.},
  date = {1963-12-01},
  journaltitle = {Journal of the Acoustical Society of America},
  shortjournal = {J. Acoust. Soc. Am.},
  doi = {10.1121/1.1918868},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {/unread},
  note = {Paper Summary: Ronald T. Verrillo's 1963 article in The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America titled Effect of Contactor Area on the Vibrotactile Threshold presents a systematic investigation into the spatial parameters governing human vibrotactile sensitivity, specifically focusing on the relationship between contactor area, frequency, and configuration. The abstract summarizes the core finding that contactor area serves as a more significant stimulus parameter than the gradient or curvature of displacement, noting that absolute vibration thresholds appear independent of frequency when very small contactors are utilized and independent of area at low frequencies, which reasonably leads to the conclusion that responses to mechanical skin displacement are mediated by more than one receptor system despite a lack of direct physiological evidence. The introduction outlines the considerable uncertainty regarding the adequate stimulus for the sense of touch and vibration, categorizing past experiments by their focus on physical domain parameters such as displacement, velocity, acceleration in the time domain, and displacement gradients or curvatures in the spatial domain, while highlighting conflicting historical results where researchers like Holway and Crozier found area dependence, Sherrick observed increased threshold curve steepness with larger areas between 100 and 300 cycles per second, and others like Nafe and Wagoner found no dependence, ultimately noting that large contactors typically produce characteristic U-shaped threshold curves whereas extremely small areas yield nearly flat curves, motivating the present report's systematic measurement of thresholds as a function of frequency, contactor area, and configuration. The preliminary experiments section describes an apparatus largely consistent with previous work wherein a sine wave generator signal was modulated, amplified, and delivered via a vibration generator mounted on a drill-press assembly allowing precise vertical adjustment to within one-thousandth of an inch, with contactors protruding into holes on a rigid surface where the subject's arm rested, and crucially, a methodological verification experiment depicted in Figure 1 utilized a circuit comprising a dry-cell battery, an oscilloscope, and the contactor to confirm skin contact, showing that while loss of contact could occur at higher intensities like 25 decibels sensation level at low frequencies as illustrated in Figure 2, absolute thresholds were determined without loss of contact, and pilot studies comparing solid, annulus, and straight-edge contactors shown in Figure 3 initially suggested the gradient or curvature of skin displacement might be more important than area. Transitioning to the final experiments designed to distinguish between area and displacement gradient control, the study employed three specific contactor types illustrated in Figure 4: a deep concave contactor filled with dental plaster impressions to match skin contours, an annulus with a solid non-vibrating rigid core to maximize gradient while minimizing area, and a shallow convex contactor to reduce gradient without altering area, with results presented in Figure 5 demonstrating that concave and convex contactors yielded corresponding similar thresholds despite differing gradients and curvatures, whereas the annulus produced generally higher thresholds attributable to its reduced area, thereby rejecting the hypothesis that gradient or curvature is the primary control factor and confirming that area of displacement emerges as the controlling parameter. To further validate the area hypothesis, a graduated series of contactors ranging from 0.005 to 5.1 square centimeters was constructed with constant gap controls, yielding absolute thresholds plotted in Figure 6 which displayed a slope of approximately 3 decibels per doubling of area, a value closely approximating hearing sensitivity trends and confirming the significance of stimulation area, while the data replotted in Figure 7 revealed that at low frequencies of 25 and 40 cycles per second the threshold is independent of area and for very small areas the threshold is independent of frequency, explaining previous discrepancies in literature where large contactors produced U-shaped curves and small ones produced flat curves, with the curves exhibiting a slope of 12 decibels below 250 cycles per second and 9 decibels above 250 cycles per second. The section addressing the question of receptor specificity analyzes these dual dependencies to propose the existence of two receptor populations, one sensitive to changes in both frequency and area and another independent of these parameters, with the former becoming increasingly dominant as area and frequency increase and the latter prevailing at low frequencies or sufficiently small areas to determine the response, contextualized by a review of the century-old controversy involving Treitel, Katz, von B\'ek\'esy, von Frey, Geldard, and Jackson regarding whether vibration and static pressure sensations arise from separate or coincident receptor systems, alongside anatomical evidence distinguishing deep layers of large-diameter heavily myelinated fibers from superficial networks of smaller diameters with light or no myelin, and noting debated encapsulated endings like the Pacinian corpuscle which demonstrated sensitivity to vibratory stimuli especially above 200 cycles per second, though direct confirmation in humans remains lacking. Finally, the summary and conclusions consolidate the findings by stating that under properly controlled conditions the area of the contactor is a controlling stimulus parameter in vibrotactile stimulation on glabrous skin, particularly above 40 cycles per second, and provide indirect evidence indicating at least two receptor systems are involved in vibrotactile sensation, one dependent on frequency and contactor area and one independent of both these parameters, effectively resolving much of the ambiguity surrounding spatial stimulus parameters in cutaneous mechanoreception.}
}

